<!-- This is the OTHER note mentioned in robots.txt — a "table of
     contents" for search engines. Since this whole website is just
     ONE single page (index.html does everything), this list only
     ever has one address in it. A bigger, multi-page site would
     list one <url> block per page instead.

     "lastmod" just means "the last time this page's content
     changed" — search engines use it as a hint for how often to
     bother re-checking the page. It's fine if this drifts out of
     date a little; nothing breaks, it just stops being a perfectly
     fresh hint.

     MOVING TO A CUSTOM DOMAIN SOMEDAY? Both this file's <loc> below
     AND the "Sitemap:" line in robots.txt hardcode today's real
     address (sverma2696.github.io/ino_website) — that's correct
     for right now, since that's the site's actual, only address.
     If a custom domain (like ino.link or similar) ever gets set up
     instead, both of those need updating to the NEW address in the
     same commit as the domain switch — a search engine trusting a
     stale <loc> here would keep pointing people at the old GitHub
     Pages URL instead of the real one. -->
<urlset xmlns="http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9">
  <url>
    <loc>https://sverma2696.github.io/ino_website/</loc>
    <lastmod>2026-07-18</lastmod>
    <changefreq>weekly</changefreq>
    <priority>1.0</priority>
  </url>
</urlset>
